occurrences.line_text: Now Cantium, which Kent we commenly inquire.
How much to her we owe, that all vs gaue,
That gaue vnto vs all, what euer good we haue.
We needes must passe (God do vs well acquight,)
Least we vnweeting hap to be fordonne:
For all that here on earth we dreadfull hold,
That is our Selfe, whom though we do not see,
Here wonnes Acrasia, whom we must surprise,
Nor the fine nets, which oft we wouen see
She hath ordaind this law, which we approue,
Too well we see, (said they) and proue too well
And we your liege men faith vnto you plight.
That now we foolish men that prayse gin eke t'enuy.
That we thus rashly through thy darkesome dore,
Farewell my sweetest sonne, sith we no more shall meet.
We mortall wights, whose liues and fortunes bee
To succour wretched wights, whom we captiued see.
We both are bound to follow heauens beheasts,
He comes not here, we scorne his foolish ioy,
Ne lend we leisure to his idle toy:
Turne we our steedes, that both in equall tilt
But thou good man, sith farre in sea we bee,
That now no more we can the maine-land see,
But why do we deuise of others ill,
Whiles thus we suffer this same dotard old,
Ere that we to efforce it do begin:
Then if all fayle, we will by force it win,
Then all the world is lost, and we in vaine haue toyld.
Till we returne againe in safetie:
Hence farre away we will blindfolded lie,
What monstrous enmity prouoke we heare,
Battell against the Gods? so we a God inuade.
And how we with our foe may come to fight.
Well know'st thou, whe[n] we friendship first did sweare,
That mongst the manie vertues, which we reed,
That we may vs reserue both fresh and strong,
We trauelled, both wearie of the way
We did alight, and sate in shadow myld;
Sith to his powre we all are subiect borne:
Mote we entreat you, sith this gentle crew
That as we ride together on our way,
Might be my lucky lot; sith all by lot we hold.
Long had the Thames (as we in records reed)
Mongst those twelue signes, which nightly we doe see
We are not sure they would so long remaine:
Till we may be assur'd they shall their course retaine.
For all we haue is his: what he list doe, he may.
There leaue we them in pleasure and repast,
And turne we here to this faire furrowes end
We on his first aduenture may him forward send.
Then this of Artegall, which here we haue to say.
Then weete ye Sir, that we two brethren be,
Great threasure sithence we did finde contained;
Which as our owne we tooke, and so it thought.
Vnto your selfe, said they, we giue our word,
That we may compasse this our enterprize?
Of whom we may at will the whole occasion know.
And turne we to the noble Prince, where late
We did him leaue, after that he had foyled
For neither will one foot, till we that carle haue hent.
If not, we will it force, maugre your foe,
But turne we now to noble Artegall;
Vpon our way, to which we weren bent,
We chaunst to come foreby a couert glade
When forward we should fare, he flat refused
So passed we, till this young man vs met,
There to their fortune leaue we them awhile,
And turne we backe to good Sir Calidore;
In stead of comfort, which we should embrace:
Which we might see after our selues remaine
But sith we need good counsell (sayd the swaine)
That we may it auenge, and punish him with speed?
But turne we now backe to that Ladie free,
Whom late we left ryding vpon an Asse,
That all this worlds gay showes, which we admire,
We should our selues demeane, to low, to hie;
That we likewise should mylde and gentle be,
So leaue we her in wretched thraldome bound,
And turne we backe to Calidore, where we him found.
And turne we backe to Calidore, where we him found.
There leaue we them in ioy, and let vs tell
O helpe thou my weake wit, and sharpen my dull tong.
Is tost with troubled sights and fancies weake,
Wretched man, wretched tree; whose nature weake,
And mightie proud to humble weake does yield,
O then too weake and feeble was the forse
Did on so weake foundation euer sit:
But ioyd weake wemens hearts to tempt, and proue
The yron walles to ward their blowes are weake & fraile.
And quickning faith, that earst was woxen weake,
To weet the cause, his weake steps gouerning,
And shame t'auenge so weake an enimy;
And that weake captiue wight now wexed strong,
For him to be yet weake and wearie well she knew.
Perceiued him to wauer weake and fraile,
And all his sinews woxen weake and raw,
Whom still she fed, whiles they were weake & young,
And the weake mind with double woe torment?
Weake wretch I wrapt my selfe in Palmers weed,
The strong through pleasure soonest falles, the weake through smart.
Weake she makes stro[n]g & stro[n]g thing does increace,
And that weake eld hath left thee nothing wise,
To succour the weake state of sad afflicted Troy.
But when strong passion, or weake fleshlinesse
Teach him the weake to strengthen, & the stro[n]g suppresse.
So me weake wretch, of many weakest one,
In their beginning they are weake and wan,
Whiles they are weake betimes with them contend:
With silly weake old woman thus to fight.
He said? Vp, vp, thou womanish weake knight,
But to weake wench did yeeld his martiall might.
Carelesse the man soone woxe, and his weake wit
Weake hands, but counsell is most strong in age.
With which weake men thou witchest, to attend:
That vitall powres gan wexe both weake and wan,
Weake body well is chang'd for minds redoubled forse.
Whilest Romanes dayly did the weake subdew:
T'allure weake trauellers, whom gotten they did kill.
Yet was the fence thereof but weake and thin;
That the weake bowes, with so rich load opprest,
Seeking the weake oppressed to relieue,
With that vpleaning on her elbow weake,
Then shall the Britons, late dismayd and weake,
And our weake hands (whom need new strength shall teach)
That the weake soule her seat did yet retaine,
But to the wound his weake hart opened wyde;
And greedy eares her weake hart from her bore:
With which he many weake harts had subdewed
That cheareful word his weake hart much did cheare,
When her weake feete could scarcely her sustaine,
That able was weake harts away to steale.
That needed much her weake age to desire,
Came forth full weake and wan, not like him selfe to bee.
And all those ioyes that weake mankind entyse.
Full weake and crooked creature seemed she,
Ere long so weake of limbe, and sicke of loue
And of weake Princes to be Patronesse,
Well did the Squire perceiue him selfe too weake,
Beholding all that womanish weake fight;
Vppon the carkasse of some beast too weake,
And all the wounded, and the weake in state,
But lies in wretched thraldome, weake and wan,
Like to a weake faint-hearted man he fared,
In the behalfe of wronged weake did fight:
Where still the stronger doth the weake deuoure,
And these weake impes replanted by thy might;
An infant, weake a kingdome to sustaine,
But now weake age had dimd his candle light.
To reskue him, and his weake part abet,
Small praise to proue your powre on wight so weake.
Besides, through sicknesse now so wan and weake,
So shew'd them her, to proue how pale & weake she was.
Or if it to reuenge he were too weake,
Seeing her weake and wan, through durance long.
She weakely started, yet she nothing drad:
The more his weakened body so to wast:
Through weakenesse of my widowhed, or woe:
Whose will her weakenesse could no way represse,
Such is the weakenesse of all mortall hope;
The strong it weakens with infirmitie,
That weakens her, and makes her party strong:
Thy weaker Nouice to performe thy will,
That weaker sence it could haue rauisht quight:
And then againe begun, My weaker yeares
Through highest heauen with weaker hand to rayne;
But in eternall woes my weaker hart
And stroue for to amaze the weaker sights;
She lightly sprinkled on his weaker parts;
As feeling wondrous comfort in her weaker eld.
That weaker wit of man could neuer reach,
Wherein his weaker wandring steps to guide,
That easie was t'inuegle weaker sight:
Or sweetnesse doth allure the weaker sence
Did driue the Romanes to the weaker side,
May often need the helpe of weaker hand;
And him selfe weaker through infirmity;
And that late weaker band of chalengers relieued.
With which my weaker patience fortune proues.
Those weaker Ladies after weary toile;
To wrong the weaker, oft falles in his owne assault.
And al the passio[n]s heale, which wou[n]d the weaker spright.
Least they should ioyne against the weaker side,
And with bold furie armes the weakest hart;
So me weake wretch, of many weakest one,
Is weakned, then thou doest him ouerronne:
His weakned powers, and dulled spirits whet,
Or weaknesse is to sinfull bands made thrall:
His powre is reft, and weaknesse doth remaine.
Our faulty weaknesse, and your matchlesse might:
Till that through weaknesse he was forst at last,
With fleshly weaknesse, which no creature may
Great weaknesse, and report of him much ill,
And changing all that forme of common weale,
And wish thee grow in worship and great weale.
Nor lawes of men, that common weales containe,
Whose wealth was want, whose ple[n]ty made him pore,
At neighbours wealth, that made him euer sad;
That like would not for all this worldes wealth:
And these rich heapes of wealth doest hide apart
Thy workes for wealth, and life for gold engage.
Though all the wealth, which is, or was of yore,
To weet, whence all the wealth late shewd by mee,
That to their people wealth they forth do well,
And often waile their wealth, which he from them did keepe.
The wealth of th'East, and pompe of Persian kings;
She to his closet went, where all his wealth
Her loue, her seruice, and her vtmost wealth.
For strength, and wealth, and happinesse she lends,
That many Princes she in wealth exceedes,
And all the wealth of rich men to the poore will draw.
Both it and all the wealth therein behight
As either might for wealth haue gotten bene,
A Ladie of great worth and wealth had beene,
And flourish in all wealth and happinesse,
For other worldly wealth they cared nought.
He through the wealth, wherein he did abound,
Through wicked pride, and wasted wealthes decay.
Of commen wealthes, of states, of pollicy,
Who through late triall, on that wealthy Strond
Of wealthy Thamis washed is along,
His weapon huge, that heaued was on hye
Againe his wonted angry weapon proou'd:
In feare to lose his weapon in his paw,
Perforce rebutted backe. The weapon bright
And drew his deadly weapon, to maintain his part.
That cursed weapon, when his cruell foes he queld.
The Prince now stood, hauing his weapon broke;
The secret vertue of that weapon keene,
And to her weapon ran, in minde to gride
Her dreadfull weapon she to him addrest,
The wicked weapon rashly he did wrest,
The wicked weapon heard his wrathfull vow,
Stand vp so long, and weapon vaine to weld,
Who being freed, from one a weapon fiercely takes.
And yeeld vnto her weapon way to pas:
The wrathfull weapon gainst his countnance bold:
With dreadfull weapon aymed at his head;
With his strange weapon, neuer wont in warre,
From the dread daunger of his weapon keene,
Out of her fist the wicked weapon caught:
He could his weapon shift from side to syde,
One time, when he his weapon faynd to shift,
He ere he could his weapon backe repaire,
His deadly weapon, which in hand he held.
Yet armes or weapon had he none to fight,
And without weapon him assayling neare,
Himselfe vnto his weapon he betooke,
He had no weapon, but his shepheards hooke,
Standing with emptie hands all weaponlesse,
And his vnready weapons gan in hand to take.
That euer warlike weapons menaged,
That downe they let their cruell weapons fall,
Hauing his warlike weapons cast behind,
Another warre, and other weapons I
But that this weapons powre I well haue kend,
For want of weapons, they shall soone be had.
And his well proued weapons to him hent;
And of his weapons did himselfe disarme.
There they dismounting, drew their weapons bold
And her welpointed weapons did about her dresse.
With murdrous weapons arm'd to cruell fight,
Ne lesse his skill in weapons did appeare,
Strokes, wounds, wards, weapons, all they did despise,
His weapons, which lay scattered all abrode,
His wonted warlike weapons all he broke,
They gan with all their weapons him assay,
With weapons in their hands, as ready for to fight.
And to them way to make, with weapons well prepard.
A raskall rout, with weapons rudely dight.
And of all other weapons lesse or more,
His weapons soone from him he threw away,
Some of their weapons, which thereby did lie,
As to his Lord, and downe his weapons layd,
He watcht in close awayt with weapons prest,
In which that wicked wight his dayes doth weare:
His fearefull friends weare out the wofull night,
For other clothes he could not weare for heat,
And with their horned feet do weare the ground,
He gaue her gold and purple pall to weare,
And on her now a garment she did weare,
The woods, the Nymphes, my bowres, my midwiues weare,
But it were that, which noblest knight on earth doth weare.
As it some Gyeld or solemne Temple weare:
Ne other tyre she on her head did weare,
And downe him smot, ere well aware he weare,
The rest of other fishes drawen weare,
Such as the Angels weare before Gods tribunall.
Some made for beasts, some made for birds to weare,
Such as false loue doth oft vpon him weare:
Out of her secret stand, that day for to out weare.
That lost faire Ladies ornament should weare,
Returned readie newes, that those same weare
And workes of noblest wits to nought out weare,
Might not the same about her middle weare.
All that her saw with wonder rauisht weare,
Those Pensifenesse did moue; and Sighes the bellows weare.
But all she did was but to weare out day.
That she vneath discerned, whether whether weare.
But with their owne repayed duely weare,
And inly wish, that in his powre it weare
But promist him, what euer wight she weare,
And talk't of pleasant things, the night away to weare.
Thus did she watch, and weare the weary night
Stood long amaz'd, as she amated weare.
He all things did puruay, which for them needfull weare.
And on his head a steele cap he did weare
Them wont to weare, and wend on foot for need,
Or of their vpper garment, which they weare:
Saw a faire damzell, which did weare a crowne
No better doe I weare, no better doe I feed.
Of that despight, neuer to wearen none;
About his neck an hempen rope he weares,
Ill weares he armes, that nill them vse for Ladies sake.
To win a willow bough, whilest other weares the bayes.
Doe pearce the rockes, and hardest marble weares;
Lets me not sleepe, but wast the wearie night
Banisht from liuing wights, our wearie dayes we waste.
One day nigh wearie of the yrkesome way,
In stead thereof he kist her wearie feet,
Dame Vna, wearie Dame, and entrance did requere.
Sad Vna downe her laies in wearie plight,
For she is wearie of the toilesome way,
As when a wearie traueller that strayes
From her nigh wearie waine, and in her armes
In westerne waues his wearie wagon did recure.
A wearie wight forwandring by the way,
His wearie limbes vpon: and eke behind,
Ere long she fownd, whereas he wearie sate,
And guide his wearie gate both too and fro:
For him to be yet weake and wearie well she knew.
Who trauels by the wearie wandring way,
Yet ceasest not thy wearie soles to lead,
Now when their wearie limbes with kindly rest,
That by the wearie way were traueiling,
That his frayle thighes nigh wearie and fordonne
His wearie pounces all in vaine doth spend,
Faint, wearie, sore, emboyled, grieued, brent
His wearie foe into that liuing well,
Of her deare knight, who wearie of long fight,
To which I meane my wearie course to bend;
There this faire virgin wearie of her way
Whiles on her wearie iourney she did ride;
And light this wearie vessell of her lode.
That long captiued soules from wearie thraldome free.
To let a wearie wretch from her dew rest,
But he, not like a wearie traueilere,
After their wearie sweat and bloudy toile,
Till at the last all breathlesse, wearie, faint
The wearie Traueiler, wandring that way,
And then by it his wearie limbes display,
And soone leaue off this toylesome wearie stoure;
To rest thy wearie person, in the shadow coole.
But taught the land from wearie warres to cease.
And wearie waxe of his continuall stay.
Till wearie of that wretched life, her selfe she hong.
Who wandring through the world with wearie feet,
Hauing their wearie limbes to perfect plight
The saluage beast embost in wearie chace,
All were he wearie of his former paine,
Lightly arose out of her wearie bed,
Did chaunce to still into her wearie spright,
But after all his warre, to rest his wearie knife.
So from the wearie spirit thou doest driue
Thus did the Prince that wearie night outweare,
Where wearie of long trauell, downe to rest
And wearie limbs a while. She nothing quaint
Her wearie Palfrey closely, as she might,
Where wearie wandring they long time did wonne,
Whom he through wearie wars and labours long,
When wearie of their sport to sleepe they fell,
Fearing least from her cage the wearie soule would flit.
Let forth his wearie ghost and made an end of strife.
His wearie ghost assoyld from fleshly band,
Like as a Snake, whom wearie winters teene,
So wearie both of fighting had their fill,
And answering their wearie turnes around,
The manner of their worke and wearie paine;
And thought his wearie limbs to haue redrest.
That at the last his wearie sprite opprest
But here my wearie teeme nigh ouer spent
And hauing me all wearie earst, downe feld,
We trauelled, both wearie of the way
And wearie limmes recur'd after late vsage bad.
T'alight, and rest their wearie limbs awhile.
To sit and rest the walkers wearie shankes,
Our wearie yokes, to gather fresher sprights,
He wearie woxe, and backe return'd againe
So well he sped him, that the wearie Beare
With wearie trauell and vncertaine toile,
Would streight dislodge the wretched wearie life.
Wearie of trauell in his former fight,
Or who did wayle or watch the wearie night?
And when I wearie am, I downe doe lay
Or wearied with bearing of her bag
And wearied his life with dull delayes:
At last dull wearinesse of former fight
His tyred armes for toylesome wearinesse,
Till faint through irkesome wearinesse, adowne
Nor wearinesse to slacke her hast, but fled
They trauel'd long, that now for wearinesse,
Who though she were with wearinesse nigh dead,
Wretchedly wearing out his youthly yeares,
Wearing a Diademe embattild wide
Who was to weet a wretched wearish elfe,
The worlds sweet In, from paine & wearisome turmoyle.
His wearisome pursuit perforce he stayd,
Weary of aged Tithones saffron bed,
Yet she her weary limbes would neuer rest,
Till weary of their way, they came at last,
From the fierce heat, and rest their weary limbs a tide.
To rest them selues, and weary powres repaire,
And to the wished hauen bring thy weary barke.
The weary soule from thence it would discharge;
His weary wagon to the Westerne vale,
The weary Britons, whose war-hable youth
Into the Ocean deepe to driue their weary droue.
Where through long watch, & late dayes weary toile,
And chaungd her weary side, the better ease to take.
The time, that mortall men their weary cares
The maistring raines out of her weary wrest,
And came at last in weary wretched plight
To find some refuge there, and rest her weary syde.
The comfort of her age and weary dayes,
After long suit and weary seruicis,
Did heape on her new waues of weary wretchednesse.
Her heart nigh broken was with weary toyle,
And lose the teme out of his weary waine,
Their garments wet, and weary armour free,
With weary pace, he farre away espide
Yet nould she d'off her weary armes, for feare
All woxen weary of their iournall toyle:
Through toylesome heate and labour of her weary fight.
There where through weary trauel she lay sleeping sou[n]d.
His weary eie returnd to him againe,
After late weary toile, which she had tride
Those weaker Ladies after weary toile;
And when my weary ghost with griefe outworne,
Or that he wexed weary of his owne,
In which they measur'd mickle weary way,
While she was flying, like a weary weft,
Her weary barke at last vppon mine Isle did rest.
Weary of toile and trauell of that day,
Thus did she watch, and weare the weary night
After that long daies toile and weary plight.
The waies, through which my weary steps I guyde,
Through all my weary trauell I haue had:
Did sleepe all night through weary trauell of his quest.
Tho wexing weary of that toylesome paine,
To which he meant his weary steps to guyde,
So that at length, after long weary chace,
To weary him the more, and waste his spight,
And weary now with carefull keeping ward,
But also trayterously did wound her weary Knight.
But being aged now and weary to
And weary of this worlds vnquiet waies,
Where soft dismounting like a weary lode,
And now she was vppon the weary way,
In sommers shade himselfe here rested weary.
His weasand pipe it through his gorget cleft:
His former paine, and wypt away his toylsoms weat.
Till merry wind and weather call her thence away.
Ne wind and weather at his pleasure call:
But let them pas, whiles wind and weather right
Till that at last the weather gan to cleare,
And of all old dislikes they made faire weather,
To weather his brode sailes, by chaunce hath spide
Of which he in faire weather wont to take great store.
The winde and weather serued them so well,
As they are wont in faire sunshynie weather,
As weather-beaten ship arriu'd on happie shore.
He gan to weaue a web of wicked guile,
With golden wyre to weaue her curled head;
Of treason, or some guilefull traine did weaue,
And faynes to weaue false tales and leasings bad,
Which oft through pride do their owne perill weaue,
Twixt life and death, long to and fro she weaued,
He gan to weaue a web of wicked guile,
Her cunning web, and spred her subtile net,
More subtile web Arachne can not spin,
Yt seemd th'enchaunted flame, which did CreÃ¼sa wed.
Till now at last relenting, she to him was wed.
And closely did her wed, but knowne to few.
Where Thames doth the Medway wedd,
So wedded th'one to Maglan king of Scots,
Whom hauing wedded as did him behoue,
The very selfe same day that she was wedded,
But to accept her to his wedded wife.
Of Thetis wedding with ï¿½acidee,
When heauie hammers on the wedge are swaid;
Into great Ingoes, and to wedges square;
But to small purpose yron wedges made;
To contract wedlock: (so the fates ordaind.)
Wedlock contract in bloud, and eke in blood
Escaped hardly, hardly praisd his wedlock good.
That was in sacred bands of wedlocke tyde
The loyall links of wedlocke did vnbind,
Of wedlocke to that new vnknowen guest:
He gaue in wedlocke to Maximian,
This daughter thought in wedlocke to haue bound
Enlincked fast in wedlockes loyall bond,
